         b'\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t<article id="post-508" class="post-508 post ty'
         b'pe-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized'
         b'">\n\t\t<header class="entry-header">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<h1 class="entr'
         b'y-title"><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/what-makes-a-strong-res'
         b'earcher/" title="Permalink to What makes a strong researcher?" rel="'
         b'bookmark">What makes a strong researcher?</a></h1>\n\t\t\t\n\t'
         b'\t\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-meta">\n\t\t\t\t<span class="sep">Post'
         b'ed on </span><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/what-makes-a-strong'
         b'-researcher/" title="9:57 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date'
         b'" datetime="2012-04-17T21:57:39+00:00" pubdate>April 17, 2012</time>'
         b'</a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span cla'
         b'ss="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.'
         b'uk/author/ucaceyl/" title="View all posts by Emmanuel" rel="author">'
         b'Emmanuel</a></span></span>\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-meta -->\n\t\t\t\n'
         b'\t\t\t\t\t</header><!-- .entry-header -->\n\n\t\t\t\t<div class="en'
         b'try-content">\n\t\t\t<p>I was flipping through Simon Reynolds latest'
         b' book &#8220;<em>Retromania: Pop Culture&#8217;s Addiction to its Ow'
         b'n Past</em>&#8221; when this paragraph caught my eyes.</p>\n<bloc'
         b'kquote><p>According to Harold Bloom&#8217;s theory of creativity, ou'
         b'tlined in books like The Anxiety of Influence and A Map of Misreadin'
         b'g, a &#8216;strong&#8217; poet is one who&#8217;s heavily influenced'
         b' by a predecessor but who resists that influence, fights it with eve'
         b'ry ounce of its strength. In Bloom&#8217;s Freudian-mystical account'
         b', the resulting Oedipal struggle entails the younger poet (who will '
         b'have been initiated, turned on to the glory of poetry by a primal en'
         b'counter with the elder&#8217;s work) swerving from the ancestor&#821'
         b'7;s style, willfully misreading it or doing violence to it in some o'
         b'ther way. The strong artist is impelled by a despairing sense of bel'
         b'atedness, the feeling that nothing new can be said because the precu'
         b'rsor said it all. A titanic psychological struggle to self-birth one'
         b'self as an artist is required before the descendant ceases to ventri'
         b'loquise the dead elder and finds his own voice. But a &#8216;weak&#8'
         b'217; poet (or painter or musician) is simply inundated, flooded by t'
         b'he ancestor&#8217;s vision.</p></blockquote>\n<p>Does this theory'
         b' about creativity applies to research? Is a strong researcher one wh'
         b'o&#8217;s been heavily influenced by predecessor&#8217;s work and ma'
         b'kes violence to it to find his or her own voice? I believe there&#82'
         b'17;s some truth in this. I do not mean that software engineering res'
         b'earch should be like poetry. I&#8217;m with Bertand Russell, I like '
         b'<a title="Bertrand Russell - Clarity and exact thinking" href="http:'
         b'//www.youtube.com/watch?v=mpJcn0Otk7I">clarity and exact thinking</a'
         b'>. There are nevertheless strong parallels between creativity in res'
         b'earch, poetry, and in fact most other kinds of creative work. All re'
         b'quire some form of obsession with your work, and an urge to explore '
         b'the unknown and move things forward.</p>\n<p>I cannot finish this'
         b' without some poetry. So here&#8217;s\xc2\xa0<a title="Niall Spoon'
         b'er-Harvey" href="http://www.whippersnapperpress.com/archives/writer/'
         b'niall-spooner-harvey">Niall Spooner-Harvey</a>, one of London&#8217;'
         b's finest contemporary poets, and his already classic &#8220;All My C'
         b"onversvatories Have Won Awards&#8221;.</p>\n<p><span class='embed"
         b"-youtube' style='text-align:center; display: block;'><iframe class='"
         b"youtube-player' type='text/html' width='584' height='359' src='http:"
         b'//www.youtube.com/embed/N7RAbdHr78A?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;fs=1&#'
         b'038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;wmode=tr'
         b"ansparent' frameborder='0'></iframe></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\t\t"
         b'\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-content -->\n\t\t\n\t\t<footer class="ent'
