         b'\t\t\t\t\t</footer><!-- #entry-meta -->\n\t</article><!-- #post-508'
         b' -->\n\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t<article id="post-455" class="post'
         b'-455 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-a'
         b'gile">\n\t\t<header class="entry-header">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<h1 class="'
         b'entry-title"><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/agile-development-a'
         b'-curse-or-a-blessing-for-requirements-engineers/" title="Permalink t'
         b'o Agile Development \xe2\x80\x93 A Curse or a Blessing for Requir'
         b'ements Engineers?" rel="bookmark">Agile Development \xe2\x80\x93 '
         b'A Curse or a Blessing for Requirements Engineers?</a></h1>\n\t'
         b'\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-meta">\n\t\t\t\t<span class="s'
         b'ep">Posted on </span><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/agile-devel'
         b'opment-a-curse-or-a-blessing-for-requirements-engineers/" title="12:'
         b'47 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2012-03-30T'
         b'12:47:25+00:00" pubdate>March 30, 2012</time></a><span class="by-aut'
         b'hor"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a cl'
         b'ass="url fn n" href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/author/ucaceyl/" tit'
         b'le="View all posts by Emmanuel" rel="author">Emmanuel</a></span></sp'
         b'an>\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-meta -->\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t</header><'
         b'!-- .entry-header -->\n\n\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-content">\n\t'
         b'\t\t<p>Last week, the BCS Requirements Engineering Specialist Grou'
         b'p organised a workshop on \xe2\x80\x9c<em><a href="http://www.res'
         b'g.org.uk/index.php/Agile2012">Agile Development \xe2\x80\x93 A cu'
         b'rse or a blessing for requirements engineers?</a></em>\xe2\x80'
         b'\x9d. This was held in a fully packed room at the BCS headquarter i'
         b'n London. By coincidence, there was another talk an agile organised '
         b'by the BCS Central London branch in the very next room, so discussio'
         b'ns in the hall were all buzzing about agile and some people were'
         b'n\xe2\x80\x99t quite sure which room to go to. The demand for inf'
         b'ormation about agile keeps growing. This is probably due to the grow'
         b'ing pressure to ditch large-scale projects with rigid contracts in f'
         b'avour of smaller-scale agile projects notably for <a href="http://ww'
         b'w.guardian.co.uk/government-computing-network/2011/mar/02/it-project'
         b's-institute-for-government-report">Government IT projects</a>, but a'
         b'lso to the still widespread misunderstanding and <a href="http://blo'
         b'g.prof.so/2012/03/no-it-is-not.html">misuse</a> of agile methods, th'
         b'e difficulty of sorting out facts from hype in many agile presentati'
         b'ons, and a legitimate concern of requirements engineers and business'
         b' analysts about the impacts that such methods would have on their wo'
         b'rk.</p>\n<p>The event kicked-off with a talk by <strong>Keith Bra'
         b'ithwaite</strong> who described how requirements are discovered in a'
         b'gile projects through user stories and acceptance tests with a great'
         b'er emphasis on conversations and less on documentation. But what mak'
         b'es a good user story? To be accepted for implementation, user storie'
         b's have to satisfy the <a href="http://xp123.com/articles/invest-in-g'
         b'ood-stories-and-smart-tasks/">INVEST</a> criteria; they must be Inde'
         b'pendent, Negotiable, Estimable, Small and Testable. To discover and '
         b'organise user stories, one typically starts from larger '
         b'\xe2\x80\x9cepic\xe2\x80\x9d and organise them in <a href="http://'
         b'www.agileproductdesign.com/blog/the_new_backlog.html">story maps</a>'
         b' that provides an end-to-end description the users\xe2\x80\x99 ta'
         b'sks and goals. Keith explained he first discovered the benefits of t'
         b'est-driven development that is central to agile development many yea'
         b'rs ago while working on system to optimise the placement of GSM ante'
         b'nna for which he was developing UML models and Z specifications. He '
         b'used this system as example to illustrate the technique of story map'
         b'ping. He contrasted this form of &#8220;low resolution model&#8221; '
         b'&#8211;a phrase that I liked&#8211; to the more detailed UML activit'
         b'y diagrams or BPMN models one could also write for such models.<'
         b'/p>\n<p>There were lots of discussions during and after the talk '
         b'questioning some of the assumptions behind agile methods. As usual, '
         b'it is impossible to go to the bottom of things in one short evening,'
         b' but I found the event interesting in teasing out different sensibil'
         b'ities on this topic, from the young enthusiasts to the veterans '
         b'who\xe2\x80\x99ve seen it all before.</p>\n<p>One thing that w'
         b'asn\xe2\x80\x99t discussed so much during the evening is the impa'
         b'ct that these changes have on the work practices of requirements eng'
         b'ineers. This is something I&#8217;d like to come back to at some poi'
         b'nt. In the meantime, I would recommend the research done by Angela M'
         b'artin, Robert Biddle and James Noble described in their pape'
         b'r \xe2\x80\x9c<a href="http://www.springerlink.com/content/r2l186'
         b'3g878r1k15/">An Ideal Customer: A Grounded Theory of Requirements El'
         b'icitation, Communication and Acceptance on Agile Projects</a'
         b'>\xe2\x80\x9d. It describes the many roles requirements engineers'
         b' play in agile projects (geek interpreter, technical liaison, negoti'
         b'ator, diplomat, customer coach, super-secretary, etc.) and the diffi'
         b'culties they face in fulfilling these roles, notably in sustaining t'
         b'he pace of having to deliver quality user stories at regular interva'
         b'l while keeping constantly engaged with both developers and large nu'
         b'mbers of stakeholders in the client organisation. It also describes '
         b'some of the practices that have emerged to try overcome to these dif'
         b'ficulties, for example by having iterations where programmers work o'
         b'n technical tasks (e.g. repaying technical debt and setting up suppo'
         b'rt tools) so that it gives customers time to think ahead, organising'
         b' customers boot camps on agile processes, and having programmers wor'
         b'k as apprentices in the customer&#8217;s organisation. These are pro'
         b'bably not enough to fully resolve the workload problem for requireme'
         b'nts engineers and customers, but they can somewhat lower their impac'
         b'ts.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-content -->\n\t\t\n\t\t<footer '
         b'class="entry-meta">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="cat-lin'
         b'ks">\n\t\t\t\t<span class="entry-utility-prep entry-utility-prep-'
         b'cat-links">Posted in</span> <a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/cate'
         b'gory/agile/" title="View all posts in Agile" rel="category tag">Agil'
         b'e</a>\t\t\t</span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t</footer>'
         b'<!-- #entry-meta -->\n\t</article><!-- #post-455 -->\n\n\t\t\t\t'
         b'\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t<article id="post-310" class="post-310 post type-pos'
         b't status-publish format-standard hentry category-collaborative-model'
         b'ling-2 category-goal-modelling-2 category-research-impact category-s'
         b'ystem-evolution">\n\t\t<header class="entry-header">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t'
         b'<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/goal-mod'
         b'elling-with-pelorus/" title="Permalink to Goal Modelling with Peloru'
         b's" rel="bookmark">Goal Modelling with Pelorus</a></h1>\n\t\t\t\n\t'
         b'\t\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-meta">\n\t\t\t\t<span class="sep">Post'
         b'ed on </span><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/goal-modelling-with'
         b'-pelorus/" title="8:59 am" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" d'
         b'atetime="2012-03-02T08:59:36+00:00" pubdate>March 2, 2012</time></a>'
         b'<span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="'
         b'author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/a'
         b'uthor/ucaceyl/" title="View all posts by Emmanuel" rel="author">Emma'
         b'nuel</a></span></span>\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-meta -->\n\t\t\t\n'
         b'\t\t\t\t\t</header><!-- .entry-header -->\n\n\t\t\t\t<div class="en'
         b'try-content">\n\t\t\t<p>The first paper on <a title="seminal paper o'
         b'n goal modelling" href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/0167-6423%2893%299'
         b'0021-G">goal-driven requirements acquisition</a> was published in 19'
         b'93. Since then, it has been followed by a very large number of resea'
         b'rch papers, a comprehensive <a href="http://eu.wiley.com/WileyCDA/Wi'
         b'leyTitle/productCd-EHEP000863.html">book</a>, and a growing number o'
         b'f industrial applications, but goal modelling is still something tha'
         b't is mostly done in universities and not so much elsewhere. In indus'
         b'try, current practices are based on use cases, process modelling, an'
         b'd user stories; you will rarely meet a requirements engineer or busi'
         b'ness analyst who knows about goal modelling. This is despite a broad'
         b' agreement that existing requirements engineering practices don&#821'
         b'7;t work so well, precisely because they focus too much on the proce'
         b'sses and the software (the how) and not enough on the goals (the why'
         b'). So how can we fix this? How can we make goal modelling more broad'
         b'ly used? <a href="http://easyweb.easynet.co.uk/iany/">Ian Alexander<'
         b'/a>, one of the early adopters, says we\xe2\x80\x99ll know we'
         b'\xe2\x80\x99ve been successful when we\xe2\x80\x99ll regularly hea'
         b'r analysts saying things like &#8220;<em>this use case relates to th'
         b'is goal</em><em> that contributes to this other goal and relies on t'
         b'his domain assumption</em>.&#8221; To achieve this, we&#8217;ll need'
         b' to simplify and communicate better the most essential ideas contain'
         b'ed in our technical research papers.</p>\n<p>With this in mind, I'
         b' was captivated by Vic Stenning&#8217;s talk &#8220;<a href="http://'
         b'www.bcs.org/content/conWebDoc/43612">Pelorus: a Tool for Business Ch'
         b'ange</a>&#8221; at a meeting of the BCS Business Change Specialist G'
         b'roup last Thursday. The talk consisted purely of discussions about g'
         b'oals, how to elaborate goal models by asking WHY and HOW questions, '
         b'how to avoid confusing goals and activities, how to identify stakeho'
         b'lders by asking WHO questions, how to define goals with measurable f'
         b'actors and targets, and how to anchor risks analysis on specific goa'
         b'ls instead of doing it in a vacuum. Every concept had an almost dire'
         b'ct relation to some of our research papers: <a href="http://www.info'
         b'.ucl.ac.be/~avl/avl-fse08.pdf">goal-driven elaboration process</a>, '
         b'<a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.letier/publications/icse02.'
         b'pdf">goal refinements</a>, <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.'
         b'letier/publications/letier-FSE04.pdf">measures of partial goal satis'
         b'faction</a>, <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.letier/publica'
         b'tions/TSE-Obstacles.pdf">obstacle analysis</a>. The only ideas I cou'
         b'ld see missing from the discussions were <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.'
         b'ac.uk/staff/e.letier/publications/Conflicts-TSE.pdf">conflict analys'
         b'is </a>and <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.letier/publicati'
         b'ons/goalSim-RE2011.pdf">reasoning about alternatives</a>.</p>\n<p'
         b'>And Pelorus even brings something new and exciting to goal modellin'
         b'g. It is a lightweight tool for <em>collaborative</em> modelling. Th'
         b'e target domain for Pelorus is the domain of business change initiat'
         b'ives. Studies show that about 50% of all such initiatives fail. Ther'
         b'e are many reasons for this, but one of the main factors is a failur'
         b'e to engage key stakeholders early enough in the design of the chang'
         b'es. Vic quoted Rosabeth Kanter: &#8220;<em>Change is disturbing when'
         b' done to us, and exhilarating when done by us</em>&#8220;&#8212;a vi'
         b'ew I agree with entirely. The focus in Pelorus is on providing a pla'
         b'tform that allows large groups of stakeholders to collectively defin'
         b'e and manage their goals for a change project. Unlike other goal mod'
         b'elling tools such as <a href="http://www.objectiver.com/index.php?id'
         b'=4">Objectiver </a>or <a href="http://jucmnav.softwareengineering.ca'
         b'/ucm/bin/view/ProjetSEG/WebHome">jUCM-Nav</a>, it is not meant to be'
         b' used for a detailed goal-oriented elaboration of complete software '
         b'requirements specifications.</p>\n<p>Pelorus is a web-based tool '
         b'with a deliberate minimalistic design. The main concept is that of g'
         b'oal, a goal can support other goals, goals must be well-defined and '
         b'measurable, and&#8212;apart from a few of other things such as the g'
         b'oal-based risk analysis&#8212; that&#8217;s it. This is goal modelli'
         b'ng stripped to its bare minimum! Keeping it simple is essential to a'
         b'llow a diverse group of stakeholders to contribute directly to its e'
         b'laboration, but it also ensures that everyone focuses on the goals a'
         b'nd noting else. This minimalistic design is reflected in a clean and'
         b' simple user interface that you can see in their <a href="http://www'
         b'.toolforchange.com/tour">videos</a>. Oh, maybe it&#8217;s a detail, '
         b'but in Pelorus goal models are not called models, they are <em><stro'
         b'ng>maps</strong></em>. This is a term that was also used by another '
         b'company <a href="http://www.kinetium.com/map/demo/demo_index.html">s'
         b'elling goal-oriented techniques</a>, so there might be something her'
         b"e.</p>\n<p><span class='embed-youtube' style='text-align:center; "
         b"display: block;'><iframe class='youtube-player' type='text/html' wid"
         b"th='584' height='359' src='http://www.youtube.com/embed/_rSmCfL7LYE?"
         b'version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;fs=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#03'
         b"8;iv_load_policy=1&#038;wmode=transparent' frameborder='0'></iframe>"
         b'</span></p>\n<p>Once the goal map has been defined, Stakeholders '
         b'continue to use Pelorus to supervise the delivery and harvesting of '
         b'the changes. This transforms the goal model in a form of &#8220;livi'
         b'ng&#8221; business case that, unlike traditional business cases that'
         b' are written once and then forgotten, can evolve throughout the chan'
         b'ge delivery. This is another interesting idea that resonates with my'
         b' current research interests on system evolution.<strong></strong></p'
         b'>\n<p>Pelorus could be a good example of how research ideas trans'
         b'fer to practice, except that Vic Stenning had never heard about goal'
         b'-oriented requirements engineering. The main influence behind Peloru'
         b's, he says, is <a href="http://wulrich.com/cst_brief.html">critical '
         b'systems thinking </a>&#8211;although, as far as I know, critical sys'
         b'tems thinking doesn&#8217;t include the kind of goal modelling appro'
         b'ach present in Pelorus. Sure enough, the concepts of goals, goal dec'
         b'omposition, measurable objectives, and perhaps even obstacles are so'
         b' common that one doesn&#8217;t need to have read or heard about goal'
         b' modelling to come up with the same ideas. Yet, during the talk, the'
         b' resemblances with the research papers and <a href="http://www.info.'
         b'ucl.ac.be/Research/Publication/2001/RE01.pdf">tutorial </a>on goal-o'
         b'riented requirements engineering was striking. One person in the aud'
         b'ience observed that these ideas are very much in the air at the mome'
         b'nt. As a researcher who sometimes has to justify the public money sp'
         b'ent on his research by showing it has an impact, I like to believe t'
         b'hat we have played at least a small role in putting these ideas in t'
         b'he air. I hope Pelorus and other similar tools will continue to push'
         b' these ideas forward.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-content -->'
